# OP-215 `a2a statusline`: cache-read only, <100ms (perf itself is
# internal/cli's own TestStatuslinePerf); here just the OP-contract: the
# seeded XR-axon-demo is `blocking: true`, which severs statusline's own
# urgent-severity path (exit 11) regardless of addressee — a non-empty,
# single-line signal. AC-601.2 (spec 07 §8) names the exit code itself as
# part of the contract ("severity exit code reflect it... exit 11"), not
# just non-empty stdout — `! exec` alone only proves "some nonzero exit"
# and would stay green even if statusline regressed to exit 1 (a hard
# error) or exit 2 (usage error) instead of 11 (severity). testscript has
# no built-in exact-exit-code assertion, so the exit code is surfaced via
# a shell wrapper (the same `exec sh -c` idiom feedback_intake_guards.txtar
# already uses) and matched on stdout.
exec sh -c 'a2a statusline; echo "exit=$?"'
stdout 'XR-axon-demo'
stdout 'exit=11'
